        <h3 class="subheader">Fairness and diversity</h3>
        
        <p>
Data-driven software has the ability to shape human behavior: it affects the
products we view and purchase, the news articles we read, the social
interactions we engage in, and, ultimately, the opinions we form. Yet, data is
an imperfect medium, tainted by errors, omissions, and biases. As a result,
discrimination shows up in many data-driven applications, such as
advertisements, hotel bookings, image search, and vendor services. Biases in
data and software risk forming, propagating, and perpetuating biases in
society. Data management research should develop tools to detect, inform, and
mitigate the effects of bias, skew, and misuse in data-driven processes.
        </p>
                            
