        <h3 class="subheader">Data quality</h3>

        <p>
        Data quality has long been a focus of data management research, but
        our data quality challenges have only grown. Data is produced at
        unprecedented rates, from sources that are broad, varied, and
        unreliable, and through large-scale processes that introduce their own
        inaccuracies (e.g., structured data extraction from unstructured
        text). Traditional data cleaning techniques identify discrepancies and
        purge datasets of errors, but they treat the manifestation of a
        problem, not its root cause. They disregard the fact that errors are
        often systemic, inherent to the process that produces the data, and
        thus will keep occurring unless the problems are corrected at their
        source. Our work offers crucial insights into data quality issues:
        instead of repairing the errors themselves, our research focuses on
        diagnosing the reasons for the errors and identifying repairs in the
        processes that produce the data.
        </p>

